Comment: 15:35: even" if this network can recognise digits pretty well, it has no idea how to draw them" My brain works like this as well. Take for instance this example: 私は日本語を勉強します I can read that sentence its(' pronounced a bit like watashi" wa nihongo o benkyo s him as " ) , but I cannot write it. When I see the first character 私 I can instantly recognise it. But ask me to write it on paper and I will probably draw something which only vaguely resembles it. I am currently learning to understand spoken and written Japanese, and I can use my knowledge of spoken Japanese to type sentences in Japanese, but I can hardly write a thing and I cannot speak it properly either since I have never practised those things. Humans are adaptive, so when we learn one task we also learn some other tasks a bit like( when we learn to listen we also vaguely learn to speak), but a neural network does not have this built in. Therefore it is a bit different from the human brain. But it is funny to see how my brain has the same problems as a neural network, at least to some degree.
